subsection.p:
The flux 2-form of \mathbf F=(P,Q,R) is \Phi_{\mathbf F} = P\,dy\wedge dz + Q\,dz\wedge dx + R\,dx\wedge dy. Take its exterior derivative:
d\Phi_{\mathbf F} \amp= dP\wedge dy\wedge dz + dQ\wedge dz\wedge dx + dR\wedge dx\wedge dy.
Only one term from each differential survives: dP\wedge dy\wedge dz = P_x\,dx\wedge dy\wedge dz, dQ\wedge dz\wedge dx = Q_y\,dy\wedge dz\wedge dx = Q_y\,dx\wedge dy\wedge dz, and dR\wedge dx\wedge dy = R_z\,dz\wedge dx\wedge dy = R_z\,dx\wedge dy\wedge dz. Therefore \boxed{ d\Phi_{\mathbf F} = (P_x+Q_y+R_z)\,dx\wedge dy\wedge dz. } So \boxed{ d\Phi_{\mathbf F} = (\nabla\cdot\mathbf F)\,dx\wedge dy\wedge dz. }

Use \mathbf F=(x,y,z). Again \nabla\cdot\mathbf F=3. So the total outward flux through the closed cylinder is
\iint_{\partial E}\mathbf F\cdot\widehat{\mathbf n}\,dS \amp= \iiint_E 3\,dV \amp= 3\pi a^2h.
Thus \boxed{ \text{total outward flux}=3\pi a^2h. }
